	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>EC background paper on the causes of the food-price crisis</h1>

			
			<h4>
												28 June 2008
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p> In the cereals sector the EC prepared two papers as background to the FAO food-crisis summit on market developments and trends for wheat and maize respectively. In the case of wheat ‘world production has stayed below world consumption … during the last six years’. Recent high prices are not a result of a sudden surge in demand, which has been increasing at a constant pace (+1%), but rather a ‘significant production shortfall in major suppliers’ (Australia has had three severe droughts in six years, culminating in production in 2007 half the level of 2003.) While production is already recovering in some areas, this is not the case amongst the traditional top five main exporters. The briefing argues for the abolition of set-aside in the EU and the ending of export taxes in Argentina, Russia and Ukraine in order to stimulate a production recovery. It warns however of continued climate-induced uncertainties. Significantly the EC analysis argues that the price fluctuations experienced recently are largely attributable to changes in ending stocks, which at the global level fell by 45% between 2001 and 2007 (from 201.6 million tonnes to 111.0 million tonnes). The EC argues that changing global stock levels have been driven by supply factors.</p><p> Figures annexed to the summary analysis show that with the exception of a single year the EU has maintained a wheat surplus, although in recent years only marginally so compared to earlier years (the annual surplus for 2005/07 was less than one-third of the annual surplus for 1996/98).</p><p> In the case of maize there has been ‘an acceleration of world consumption’ since 2003, driven by biofuel policies and increased imports from China and Mexico, linked to expanding livestock production. Since 2002 global consumption of maize has increased by 143.3 million tonnes, a 22.8% increase. Production has grown by 27% over the same period (+163.5 million tonnes), albeit from a strong deficit position in 2002. Since 1999 annual demand has consistently exceeded annual production at the global level. This has led to a rapid decline in stocks (- 47% since 1999, down from 193.6 million tonnes to 102.7 million tonnes) and rising prices (up from an average of US$99.27 per tonne to US$163.66. per tonne)</p><p> However, rising prices have led to ‘a strong supply response in the USA, China, Brazil and Argentina’. Somewhat surprisingly, despite greatly expanded biofuel demand the USA has been increasing maize exports. This has been achieved by increasing production and running down stocks. Production has also increased in most major exporters, while China’s exports have been fluctuating, but on a downward trend.</p><p> According to the EC analysis ‘price fluctuations in maize can be attributed to changes in ending stocks, which up to 2002 were mainly driven by supply factors’. Between 1999 and 2007 global ending stocks fell 47% (from 193.6 million tonnes to 102.7 million tonnes).</p><p> In terms of the EU’s role, figures annexed to the summary analysis show EU production consistently below consumption (except for 2002 and 2004), despite a major expansion of annual EU maize production from 1997 onwards. Approximately 80% of EU maize consumption is as animal feed. EU net imports of maize increased dramatically in 2006 and 2007 reaching over four times the average annual level of the 1998-2001 period. </p><p> Meanwhile USDA reports indicate that the EU is expected to resume its role as a global net exporter of wheat and coarse grains’. This is expected despite ‘internal market prices in the EU [being] … two to three times above the intervention support price (€101)’. However this depends on whether the EC will approve export licences, which will depend on the level of this year’s harvest. The USDA is also reporting maize prices hitting new highs in the face of bad weather affecting harvests and the continued surge in demand for corn as an animal feed and biofuel input.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p> ‘The causes of the food price crisis: maize’, EC, AGRI-G1</p><p>

<a href="http://ec.europa.eu/agriculture/analysis/perspec/foodprice/maize_en.pdf" target="_self">http://ec.europa.eu/agriculture/analysis/perspec/foodprice/maize_en.pdf</a> <br/> </p><p> ‘The causes of the food price crisis: wheat’, EC <i> </i>AGRI-G1</p><p>

<a href="http://ec.europa.eu/agriculture/analysis/perspec/foodprice/wheat_en.pdf" target="_self">http://ec.europa.eu/agriculture/analysis/perspec/foodprice/wheat_en.pdf</a> <br/> </p><p> USDA FAS FG 06-08, June 2008</p><p>

<a href="http://www.fas.usda.gov/grain/circular/2008/06-08/grainfull06-08.pdf" target="_self">http://www.fas.usda.gov/grain/circular/2008/06-08/grainfull06-08.pdf</a> <br/> </p><p><i>BBC</i>, June 11th 2008</p><p>

<a href="http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/business/7447582.stm" target="_self">http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/business/7447582.stm</a> <br/> </p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p> With regard to wheat-sector trends two policy development should be noted: first the EU’s policy of deliberately reducing public storage of surpluses, so as to reduce the incentive for farmers to produce for intervention and make farming decisions more market oriented and second the impact of biofuels policy on the relative price incentives between wheat and coarse-grain production.</p><p> With regard to the EU policy on public stocks, between 2004 and 2007 EU ending-stocks of wheat declined by 40%, with this decline accounting for fully 27% of the decline in global wheat stocks (the USA in contrast accounted for only 16.8% of the decline). The EU emphasis on making farming decisions more responsive to world market signals is likely to increase EU participation in the global cereals trade (both as an exporter and importer). The decline in public stock holdings and growth in global trade increases the scope for financial speculation around basic agricultural commodities, a development exacerbated by the credit crunch. Given increased climatic uncertainties this is likely to throw up a new set of problems for developing countries in attaining food-security objectives.</p><p> The role that stock levels are playing in price fluctuations may require a reformulation of global policies on gain stocks.</p>
		</div>
		
